The paper deals with computational complexity issues in coalitional games, which is a topic that falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). The paper also discusses the computation of worth functions for coalitional games, which involves algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of computer science techniques to analyze solution concepts, such as the core, kernel, and bargaining set, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the paper provides results on graph games and marginal contribution nets, which are topics related to discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
